item.title: Khalida Brohi Common reading Invited Lecture
item.dc:creator: emma.epperly
item.excerpt:encoded:
Khalida Brohi, Pakistani activist for womenÕs rights, global speaker, and founder of the Sughar Empowerment Society and Foundation to help educate and empower women.
during the tenth annual Washington State University Common Reading Invited Lecture on Tuesday, Sept. 27, 2016 at the Compton Union Building in Pullman.
This year's common reading book is by Pakistani activist, Malala Yousafzai, the author of I Am Malala: The Girl Who Stood Up for Education and Was Shot by the Taliban, this yearÕs common reading book for thousands of WSU first-year and other students at campuses in Pullman, Tri-Cities, Spokane, and Puget Sound/Everett, and the Global Campus.

item.title: luis-cortes-romero_dinner-with-students
item.dc:creator: daniel.rieck
item.excerpt:encoded: Above: Immigration attorney and DACA recipient Luis Cortes Romero spoke on campus about his experiences arguing the November 2019 DACA case before the United States Supreme Court. His talk on March 2 was preceded by dinner with students from WSU’s Crimson Group and Mariposas Undocumented Alliance (pictured above). This talk was sponsored by the WSU Common Reading Program, the Crimson Group, the Pullman League of Women Voters, and the University of Idaho College of Law (from which Cortes Romero is a 2013 graduate).
